<header>
    <h1>Elementary Literacy Intro</h1>
    <p>Module 1: Phonological Awareness (Kindergarten)</p>
</header>

<div class="container">
    <main>
        <section class="card">
            <h2>1. What is Phonological Awareness?</h2>
            <p>Phonological awareness is the ability to recognize and manipulate the spoken parts of words (syllables, onset-rime, and phonemes). It is an <strong>auditory skill</strong> that does not require printed letters.</p>
            <div class="visual-aid">
                [Visual: Diagram showing Ear ➔ Sound Waves ➔ Brain processing Rhymes & Syllables]
            </div>
            <p><em>Note: This is distinct from Phonics, which connects sounds to print.</em></p>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
            <h2>2. The Science of Reading</h2>
            <p>Research from the National Reading Panel (2000) indicates:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Phonological awareness is a <strong>top predictor</strong> of early reading success.</li>
                <li>Explicit instruction significantly improves reading and spelling development.</li>
                <li>It acts as the foundation upon which phonics instruction is built.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
            <h2>3. Skill Progression Ladder</h2>
            <p>Click the stages below to see how skills develop from simple to complex:</p>
            <div class="progression-container">
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-header">
                        1. Rhyme & Alliteration
                        <span class="step-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="step-content">
                        <p><strong>Age 3-4:</strong> Recognizing matching sounds at the ends or beginnings of words (e.g., "Cat, Bat, Hat").</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-header">
                        2. Sentence Segmentation
                        <span class="step-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="step-content">
                        <p><strong>Age 4-5:</strong> Hearing individual words within a spoken sentence.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-header">
                        3. Syllables
                        <span class="step-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="step-content">
                        <p><strong>Age 5 (Kindergarten):</strong> Clapping or counting parts of a word (e.g., "El-e-phant" = 3).</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-header">
                        4. Onset & Rime
                        <span class="step-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="step-content">
                        <p><strong>Age 5.5:</strong> Splitting a syllable into start (onset) and end (rime). Example: /b/ - /at/.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-header">
                        5. Phonemes (The Goal!)
                        <span class="step-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="step-content">
                        <p><strong>Age 6+:</strong> Manipulating individual sounds. Blending (/c/ /a/ /t/ -> cat) and Segmenting (cat -> /c/ /a/ /t/).</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="card">
            <h2>4. Instructional Example: "The Sound Game"</h2>
            <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Students will blend onsets and rimes to form words.</p>
            <table>
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Step</th>
                        <th>Teacher Action (Script)</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>I Do</strong></td>
                        <td>"Listen to these parts: /s/ ... /un/. What is the word? Sun."</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>We Do</strong></td>
                        <td>"Let's try one together. /m/ ... /ap/. Say it with me. Map!"</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>You Do</strong></td>
                        <td>"Your turn. /f/ ... /ish/. What is the word?" (Students: Fish!)</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </section>
    </main>

    <aside>
        <div class="quick-fact">
            <h4>Recommended Time</h4>
            <span class="big-stat">10-15</span>
            <p>Minutes Daily</p>
            <small>Brief, brisk, consistent practice is best.</small>
        </div>
        
